value.value: Distension of the renal pelvis by accumulated fluid or urine.
Malignant tumor of striated muscle or pluripotential mesenchymal stem cells composed mainly of small round cells, with some partial skeletal muscle differentiation.
Failure of two or more structures ( not voids or lumens) to join together.
Malignant mesenchymal tumor that morphologically and phenotypically resembles embryonal skeletal muscle.

definition.value: Most often used in the context of bone.

value.value: Generally benign germ cell derived tumors of male or female containing derivatives from all three germ layers with differentiation in the malignant form being poor. Pre-sacral tumors located in the retrorectal space between the rectum and the sacrococcygeal part of the spine.

Increase in the rate of growth of an organism, organ or tissue as a consequence of increased proliferation, reduced cell death, or a combination. Not due to an increase in cell size; see Hypertrophy MPATH: 159.

Generally benign germ cell derived tumors of male or female containing derivatives from all three germ layers with differentiation in the malignant form being poor. Sacrococcygeal tumors are located at the base of the coccyx.
Benign stromal tumors of the soft tissue with skeletal muscle differentiation.
Systemic manifestation of MPATH: 407.
Dermal, subcutaneous,  or tendinous lesions characterized by accumulations of lipid-laden macrophages often rich in cholesterol.
The cessation of fetal or embryonic growth beyond a particular stage.
A uterus distended with a fluid containing large quantities of mucin.
Thickening of the cementum layer of the molars.

definition.value: This is usually a normal adaptive response, serving to improve the functional properties of teeth during aging.
A variety of cysts develop in the ovary. They are subdivided based on where they develop anatomically. Ovarian follicles in this case become large and fluid filled.
The uterus of older female mice often becomes distended with numerous fluid filled cysts that extend from the endometrium.

value.value: Extravascular blood between retina and choroid

A focal malformation resembling a neoplasm which results from faulty development of an organ; composed of an abnormal mixture of tissue elements, or an abnormal proportion of a single element. Growth and location are usually normal for that tissue cf. Heterotopia/Choristoma MPATH:76/MPATH:477.
Tiny yellow or white deposits of  lamellar or amorphous extracellular material that build up between retina and retinal pigment epithelium.
An increase in size of the spleen.
Rupture of the intervertebral disc, usually dorsally to compress the spinal cord, secondary to trauma.

definition.value: These become more common with age.

value.value: Accumulation of clear large vacuoles in hepatocytes (most likely lipid pending frozen sections and oil red O or other lipid stains) around central veins.
Release of melanin pigment in the dermis.

definition.value: Observed as melanin pigment within macrophages in the dermis. Inflammation in the epidermis stimulates melanocytes to increase the synthesis of melanin and subsequently to transfer the pigment to surrounding keratinocytes. If the basal layer is injured (e.g. lichen planus), melanin pigment is released and subsequently trapped by macrophages in the papillary dermis.

value.value: Degenerative changes in skeletal muscle including hyalinization, swelling, fragmentation, vacuolation eventually resulting in death of muscle fibers.
Fragmentation and erosion of articular cartilage.
Pink amorphous material (amyloid) deposited within the renal tubules.
An old organized thrombus that has been recanalized to permit blood flow.
Various degrees of pulmonary interstitial fibrosis.
